Generating codewords.
We use BCH coding algorithm to generate codewords. The BCH coding is chosen because it provides the codes with a wide range of the message and code lengths. The choice of the coding algorithm is, however, not crucial to our work and our method works with other ECC algorithms as well.
We generated codewords of lengths 127,255127255127,255 and 511511511, where the code lengths are chosen to be smaller than the number of users (1,00010001,000) to emulate the setting with a very large number of users. For each code length, we find the message length of greater than or equal to 646464 that produces a valid code. Table 1 shows the code statistics.

Training setup.
We train the UV models using the FedAvg method with 111 local epoch and 20,0002000020,000 rounds with 0.010.010.01 of users selected at each round.
Table 2 provides the network architectures used for each dataset. In models, we use Group Normalization (GN) instead of batch-normalization (BN) following the observations that BN does not work well in non-iid data setting of federated learning (Hsieh et al., 2019).
Models are trained with SGD optimizer with learning rate of 0.10.10.1 and learning rate decay of 0.010.010.01.
